# FUNCTION TO RETRIEVE URLS FROM ONE PAGE

def one_page_links(url):
    soup = BeautifulSoup((requests.get(url)).text, "html.parser")
    articles = soup.find_all("h2")
    return([x.find_all("a")[0]["href"] for x in articles])

The following function generalizes the above function to work for the desired amount of pages. </font>

In [4]:
# FUNCTION TO RETRIEVE URLS FROM ONE OR MORE PAGES
# URL NEEDS TO HAVE THE FORWARD /
def extract_links(url, page=1):
    if page == 1:
        return(one_page_links(url))
    if page > 1:
        pages_wanted = [url+"page/"+str(x)+"/" for x in range(1,page+1)]
        all_articles = [one_page_links(page) for page in pages_wanted]
        return([item for sublist in all_articles for item in sublist])

I tested my function for the following article lists: (1) science, (2) sports, and (3) opinion. </font>

This function gets article info. The parameter is the URL for a given article. I have some error handling, just in case some of the articles were formatted differently. </font>

In [6]:
def get_article_info(url):
    # PARSING
    this_request = requests.get(url).text
    abc_soup = BeautifulSoup(this_request, "html.parser")
    article_body = abc_soup.find_all("div", {"itemprop", "articleBody"})
    entry_content = abc_soup.find_all("div", {"class", "entry-content"})[0]

    # AUTHOR
    article = str([s.text for s in abc_soup.findAll("div") if s.get("itemprop") == "articleBody"])
    try:
        author = re.split("Written [Bb]y: ", article, re.IGNORECASE)[1]
        author = re.split("\\", author.encode('ascii', 'ignore'))[0]
    except:
        try:
            m = re.search("Written [Bb]y: [A-z]{1,14} [A-z]{3,15}", abc_soup.text)
            author = m.group(0)
            author = re.split("Written [Bb]y: ", author)[1]
        except:
            author = np.NaN

    # TITLE
    try:
        title = abc_soup.find_all("h1", {"class": "entry-title"})[0].text.encode('ascii', 'ignore')
    except:
        try:
            title = article_body.find_all("strong")[0].text.encode('ascii', 'ignore')
        except:
            title = np.NaN
        
    # ENTRY
    paragraphs = [entry_content.find_all("span", { "style" : "font-weight: 400;" })[x].text for x in range(len(entry_content.find_all("span", { "style" : "font-weight: 400;" })))]
    entry = "".join(paragraphs[:-1]).strip()
    entry = entry.encode('ascii', 'ignore')

    this_dic = {"author": author, "text": entry, "title": title, "url": url}
    return(this_dic)

stemmer = PorterStemmer().stem
tokenize = nltk.word_tokenize

def stem(tokens,stemmer = PorterStemmer().stem):
    return [stemmer(w.lower()) for w in tokens] 

def lemmatize(text):
    """
    Extract simple lemmas based on tokenization and stemming
    Input: string
    Output: list of strings (lemmata)
    """
    return stem(tokenize(text))

# RETURNS COUNTER CLASS
def get_em_tokens(some_text):
    # INITIALIZE TOKENIZER
    tokenizer = RegexpTokenizer(r'\w+')

    # MY STOP WORDS
    stops = STOPWORDS
    more_stopwords = set(["said", "will", "really", "going", "might", "also", "come", "don't", "in", "UC", "Davis", "student", "students", "year", "city", "campus", "Day", "new", "News", "Last", "week", "Logs"])
    stops = set(stops).union(more_stopwords)

    # REMOVE STOP WORDS FROM TOKENS
    tokens_no_stop = [i for i in tokenizer.tokenize(some_text) if not i in stops]
    
    # LEMMATIZE THE TOKENS
    lemmata = [lemmatize(x) for x in tokens_no_stop]
    lemmata2 = [item for sublist in lemmata for item in sublist]
    
    return Counter(lemmata2)

Finding the Top 3 Article Pairs¶

<font size=4.5> I chose specific stopwords on top of the stopwords from wordcloud. </font>

In [23]:
# MY STOP WORDS
stopwords = STOPWORDS
more_stopwords = set(["said", "will", "really", "going", "might", "also", "come", "don't", "in", "UC", "Davis", "student", "students", "year", "city", "campus", "Day", "new", "News", "Last", "week", "Logs"])
stopwords = set(stopwords).union(more_stopwords)

<font size=4.5> I used the TfidfVectorizer function to create a sparse matrix. </font>

In [24]:
# CREATE CORPUS
corpus_raw = ". ".join(news_df.text)

# INITIALIZE STEMMER
st = nltk.stem.LancasterStemmer()
corpus = set([st.stem(words) for words in nltk.tokenize.word_tokenize(corpus_raw)])

# VECTORIZE THIS CORPUS
vect = TfidfVectorizer(sublinear_tf=True, max_df=0.5, analyzer='word',stop_words=stopwords,vocabulary=corpus)
vect.fit(corpus)

# FUNCTION TO TOKENIZE
def getStems(doc):
    stems = set([st.stem(words) for words in nltk.tokenize.word_tokenize(doc)])
    return(stems)
In [25]:
# GENERATES AND CALCULATES COSINE SIMILARITY SCORES
def getSparseMatrices(doc1,doc2):
    #print(len(doc1)+len(doc2))
    stems=[getStems(d) for d in [doc1,doc2]]
    doc1_vec=np.sum(vect.transform(stems[0]).toarray(),axis=0)
    doc2_vec=np.sum(vect.transform(stems[1]).toarray(),axis=0)
    cos_sim=np.dot(doc1_vec.T,doc2_vec)/(np.linalg.norm(doc1_vec)*np.linalg.norm(doc2_vec))
    return(cos_sim)

<font size=4.5> Let's create a pairwise similarity matrix where the diagonals are 0.

WARNING: The following function in particular takes a long time to run. </font>

In [26]:
# WARNING: UNCOMMENT THIS AFTER IT IS DONE LOADING
# WARNING: THIS TAKES A LONG TIME TO LOAD

# GETS THE SIMILARITY MATRIX WE WANT TO WORK WITH
sim_mat=[[getSparseMatrices(row,col) for row in news_df.text] for col in news_df.text]
In [27]:
# CREATES MATRIX AND SETS DIAGONALS TO 0
similarity = np.array(sim_mat).reshape(120, 120)
np.fill_diagonal(similarity, 0)
# similarity

<font size=4.5> Now, we will triangularize to remove duplicate pairs, then catch any duplicates that have been posted more than once on listing or cross-posted using the for loop below. </font>

In [28]:
# TRIANGULARIZE TO REMOVE DUPLICATES
sim_triangle = np.triu(similarity)
# print sim_triangle

# ERROR CATCHING
for i in range(len(sim_triangle)):
    for j in range(len(sim_triangle[i])):
        try:
            if round(sim_triangle[i][j],2) == 1:
                sim_triangle[i][j] = 0
        except:
            if sim_triangle[i][j] == 1:
                sim_triangle[i][j] = 0

closest_article = np.argsort(sim_triangle)[:,119]
top_score = np.sort(sim_triangle)[:,119]

Check if authors are the same to see if Algorithm is Working¶

<font size=4.5> In the above dataframe, I documented the authors. I will check if the authors are the same for similar articles. We should have a solid percentage of authors who are the same according to similarity scores. </font>

from __future__ import division

# SEE WHERE AUTHORS ARE THE SAME
sim_df["same_author"] = (sim_df["author"] == sim_df["sim_author"])

(len(sim_df[sim_df["same_author"] == True])/120) * 100
